Define some `rotationSpeed` field:

    public float rotationSpeed = 90f;

Use [`Quaternion.LookRotation`](https://docs.unity3d.com/ScriptReference/Quaternion.LookRotation.html) to get the `Quaternion` you want to rotate towards. You want the local forward to point in the global forward direction and local up to point towards the target position, so use `Quaternion.LookRotation(Vector3.forward,targetDirection)`:

    public IEnumerator LookAt(Vector2 position) {
        // casting to Vector2 and normalizing is redundant
        Vector3 targetDirection = position - transform.position; 
        Quaternion targetRotation = Quaternion.LookRotation(Vector3.forward, targetDirection);

Then use [`Quaternion.RotateTowards`](https://docs.unity3d.com/ScriptReference/Quaternion.RotateTowards.html) with the max amount of degrees you want to rotate in that frame until you are done rotating toward the goal rotation:

    while (Quaternion.Angle(targetRotation, transform.rotation) &gt; 0.01) 
    {
        transform.rotation = Quaternion.RotateTowards(transform.rotation, targetRotation,
                time.deltaTime * rotationSpeed);
    }

Altogether:

    public float rotationSpeed = 90f;

    public IEnumerator LookAt(Vector2 position) {
        // casting to Vector2 and normalizing is redundant
        Vector3 targetDirection = position - transform.position; 
        Quaternion targetRotation = Quaternion.LookRotation(Vector3.forward, targetDirection);

        while (Quaternion.Angle(targetRotation, transform.rotation) &gt; 0.01) 
        {
            transform.rotation = Quaternion.RotateTowards(transform.rotation, targetRotation,
                    time.deltaTime * rotationSpeed);
        }
    }

