Type initialisers aka static constructors are called once, even when they throw and [Static Constructors (C# Programming Guide)](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/programming-guide/classes-and-structs/static-constructors) says it explicitely.

&gt; If a static constructor throws an exception, the runtime will not invoke it a second time, and the type will remain uninitialized for the lifetime of the application domain in which your program is running.

This can be demonstrated easily with the following code.

```
public static int i = 0;
public static async Task Main()
{
    try { new X(); } catch (TypeInitializationException e) { Console.WriteLine(e.GetBaseException().Message); }

